hire, England, United Kingdom","Thorp Arch, Yorkshire, England":"Thorp Arch, Yorkshire, England","Congleton, Cheshire, England":"Congleton, Cheshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Davenport","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): habitational name from a place in Cheshire named Davenport, from the Dane river (apparently named with a Celtic cognate of Middle Welsh <i>dafnu</i> ‘to drop, to trickle’) + Old English <i>port</i> ‘market town’.","Irish: in Tipperary, this is an English surname adopted by bearers of Munster Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donndubhartach</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’ + <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>artach</i> ‘nobleman’.","History: John Davenport (died 1670) arrived in Boston, MA, in 1637. He came of an English Cheshire family associated with Capesthorne Hall, near Macclesfield."],"variants":[{"name":"Devenport","meanings":["English and Irish (Lancashire): variant of   Davenport  . The spelling <b>Devonport</b> is found in Ireland and it may have been this form which gave rise to <i>Devenport</i>."]},{"name":"Dunworth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamon, Niall.","Irish: adopted in Ireland by bearers of Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> (see   Davenport   2).","English: perhaps a variant of <b>Dungworth</b>, see   Dunsworth  ."]}]},{"name":"Ormus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: nickname from the Christian liturgic Latin phrase <i>oremus</i> ‘let us pray’, probably applied to someone who used this phrase in difficult situations. As a noun <i>oremus</i> became a metaphor for troubles.","Croatian (<b>Oremuš</b>): from the personal name <i>Oremuš</i>, regional vernacular form of Latin   Hieronymus  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hieronymus","meanings":["form of Greek <i>Hieronymos</i> (  see  <b>Jerome</b>   ), still used in Germany, especially in Catholic Bavaria and the Rhineland."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":20,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":40,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":50,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A serie